[30;1m199 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m200 | [0m[35m//! A list is a doubly linked list. That is, it is a Sequence that supports both[0m
[30;1m201 | [0m[35m//! forward and backward traversal, and (amortized) constant time insertion and[0m
[30;1m202 | [0m[35m//! removal of elements at the beginning or the end, or in the middle. Lists have[0m
[30;1m203 | [0m[35m//! the important property that insertion and splicing do not invalidate iterators[0m
[30;1m204 | [0m[35m//! to list elements, and that even removal invalidates only the iterators that point[0m
[30;1m205 | [0m[35m//! to the elements that are removed. The ordering of iterators may be changed[0m

[30;1m1727 | [0m[35m        result = d_arr.get()[()][0m

[30;1m72 | [0m[35mThe CUDA programming guide says great things about :command:`nvcc` and how[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35mit will unroll loops for you. As of Version 2.1, that's simply not true, and[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35m``#pragma unroll`` is simply a no-op, at least according to my experience.[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mWith metaprogramming, you can dynamically unroll your loops to the needed[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35msize in Python.[0m
